  "confidence": "high",
  "text": "Ra emphasizes inner practice more than external technique. Core recommendations are regular meditation/contemplation/prayer, honest self-inquiry to integrate mind/body/spirit, and living each moment in alignment with service-to-others. These form the foundation; techniques follow from that center of unity and love.\n\n\n\nConcrete, practical steps you can use now:\n- Daily sitting practice: 10–30 minutes of meditation or contemplative prayer each morning and/or evening to reverse analytical habits and allow integration. Focus simply on being with your self, observing without judgment.  \n- Devoted self-inquiry: Keep a short journal noting situations that trigger strong emotion or reaction. Reflect on those as lessons about the self rather than events to blame; practice asking, “What is this teaching me about love or separation?”  \n- Embody service moment-to-moment: Intentionally choose one small, kind action each day (listening fully, helping a task, offering a calm presence). Over time expand this into a habit of living “as it is,” letting daily behavior reflect your orientation toward others.\n\n\n\nPractical balancing note: when compassion arises, apply strict honesty and examine whether wisdom or another quality is needed to prevent imbalance. Work with small experiments (compassion plus clear boundary; compassion with inquiry) and journal results to refine your discernment.\n\nOne next step: commit to a two-week experiment of 10 minutes daily meditation plus one conscious act of service each day, then review your journal for changes in feeling and insight. Would you like a simple 10‑minute meditation outline to begin?",
