  "text": "I'm sorry you’re carrying this weight. Depression can make meaning feel distant and life hollow; that response is understandable and human. You don’t have to rush past the pain or pretend it isn’t real to work with it spiritually.\n\nRa speaks to emotional pain as a common catalyst offering lessons like patience and tolerance, and suggests that when pain isn’t integrated it can deepen until more opportunities for learning are given.\n\n\n\nPractically, Ra’s framing invites a gentle, stepwise approach: acknowledge the pain rather than resisting it, allow yourself to feel without self-judgment, and look for small ways the experience can inform your growth. That does not mean minimizing the need for help. If you aren’t already, please consider reaching out to a mental-health professional or trusted support person. Alongside professional care, two simple, Ra-aligned practices you might try are: (1) daily 5–10 minutes of reflective journaling where you let feelings surface and name them without fixing them, and (2) one small act of service or kindness each week (even a brief supportive note to someone) to shift focus outward and reconnect with purpose.\n\nIf you’d like, we can explore a short journaling template together, or find passages in Ra that speak to loneliness, service, or practical ways to work with catalyst. Which would help you most right now?",
